# Summary Points

- A **time series** is data collected at regular time intervals. The `ts()` function tells R that your data has a time dimension.
- `frequency` tells R how many observations make up one full cycle (12 = monthly, 4 = quarterly).
- `start=c(year, period)` tells R when the series begins.
- Every time series is made up of **Trend**, **Seasonal**, and **Random** components.
- Use **additive** decomposition when seasonal variation is constant; use **multiplicative** when it grows with the trend.
- `decompose()` automatically separates these components using moving averages.
- You can **subtract** any component from the series to study the rest in isolation — this is called **adjustment**.
- `diff()` computes changes between time periods — important for stationarity (covered in later labs).

